<figureCitation id="F6D62A4CFF9E463576F3FDADFC99FD43" box="[743,845,603,629]" captionStart-0="Fig" captionStart-1="Fig" captionStartId-0="3.[189,232,1856,1882]" captionStartId-1="4.[189,232,1690,1716]" captionTargetBox-0="[222,1334,283,1811]" captionTargetBox-1="[189,1400,265,1652]" captionTargetId-0="figure-11@3.[203,1383,265,1818]" captionTargetId-1="figure-14@4.[189,1400,265,1652]" captionTargetPageId-0="3" captionTargetPageId-1="4" captionText-0="Fig. 1. Hemipogon trilobatus Bitencourt &amp; Rapini sp. nov. A. Habitus. B. Cyme with two flowers and a bud. C. Flower. D. Flower with calyx and two corolla lobes removed to show the gynostegium. E. Corolla lobe, adaxial view. F. Anther with a staminal corona lobe basally attached. G. Corona lobe showing the 3-lobed apex, adaxial view. H. Gynostegium, viewed from above. I. Pollinarium. Drawn by Pétala Gomes Ribeiro from the holotype (IBGE[33546])." captionText-1="Fig. 2. Habitat and distribution of Hemipogon trilobatus Bitencourt &amp; Rapini sp. nov. A. Open savannah in Chapada dos Veadeiros, state of Goiás, Brazil. Photo by CB. B. Map showing the geographic distribution of H. trilobatus sp. nov. in the Cerrado domain (shaded area at reference map in A) and its occurrence (black star) nearby the Chapada dos Veadeiros National Park. Images and distribution maps were built and exported using ArcGIS online (https://www.arcgis.com). © Esri and its licensors, all rights reserved." figureDoi-0="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.4316944" figureDoi-1="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.4316946" httpUri-0="https://zenodo.org/record/4316944/files/figure.png" httpUri-1="https://zenodo.org/record/4316946/files/figure.png" pageId="2" pageNumber="3">Figs 1–2</figureCitation>
</paragraph>
