<paragraph id="6E5236C9FF9E463574A9F895FBE9F8DF" blockId="2.[189,1400,1890,2025]" pageId="2" pageNumber="3">
<taxonomicName id="A9ED4D4AFF9E463574A9F895FE16F84A" authority="Bitencourt &amp; Santos &amp; Snak &amp; Rapini, 2020" authorityName="Bitencourt &amp; Santos &amp; Snak &amp; Rapini" authorityYear="2020" box="[189,450,1890,1916]" class="Magnoliopsida" family="Apocynaceae" genus="Hemipogon" kingdom="Plantae" order="Gentianales" pageId="2" pageNumber="3" phylum="Tracheophyta" rank="species" species="trilobatus" status="sp. nov.">
<emphasis id="5C99EADBFF9E463574A9F895FE16F84A" box="[189,450,1890,1916]" italics="true" pageId="2" pageNumber="3">Hemipogon trilobatus</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
<taxonomicNameLabel id="47AA57A0FF9E463575D8F894FDFEF84A" box="[460,554,1890,1916]" pageId="2" pageNumber="3" rank="species">sp. nov.</taxonomicNameLabel>
is known from a small population nearby the S„o Bento waterfall, in Chapada dos Veadeiros, 
<collectingRegion id="AC29F82BFF9E463575F7F870FDFEF896" box="[483,554,1926,1952]" country="Brazil" name="Goias" pageId="2" pageNumber="3">Goiás</collectingRegion>
, 
<collectingCountry id="16FA7659FF9E4635762DF870FD55F896" box="[569,641,1926,1952]" name="Brazil" pageId="2" pageNumber="3">Brazil</collectingCountry>
(
<figureCitation id="F6D62A4CFF9E46357687F870FD09F896" box="[659,733,1926,1952]" captionStart="Fig" captionStartId="4.[189,232,1690,1716]" captionTargetBox="[189,1400,265,1652]" captionTargetId="figure-14@4.[189,1400,265,1652]" captionTargetPageId="4" captionText="Fig. 2. Habitat and distribution of Hemipogon trilobatus Bitencourt &amp; Rapini sp. nov. A. Open savannah in Chapada dos Veadeiros, state of Goiás, Brazil. Photo by CB. B. Map showing the geographic distribution of H. trilobatus sp. nov. in the Cerrado domain (shaded area at reference map in A) and its occurrence (black star) nearby the Chapada dos Veadeiros National Park. Images and distribution maps were built and exported using ArcGIS online (https://www.arcgis.com). © Esri and its licensors, all rights reserved." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.4316946" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/4316946/files/figure.png" pageId="2" pageNumber="3">Fig. 2</figureCitation>
). It grows in open savannah and wet grasslands locally known as “várzea” and was collected with flowers in August and September. The species has not been found since a fire burned the 
<typeStatus id="B156886BFF9E46357607F839FD92F8DF" box="[531,582,1999,2025]" pageId="2" pageNumber="3">type</typeStatus>
locality (M.A. da Silva, pers. com., 2015).
</paragraph>
